      { q:"Which drug is approved only for SHORT-term use (under 3 months)?", opts:["Orlistat","Liraglutide 3.0 mg","Phentermine","Naltrexone-bupropion"], ans:2, exp:"Phentermine is approved for short-term use (<3 months); the five long-term options include orlistat, lorcaserin, phentermine-topiramate, naltrexone-bupropion, and liraglutide 3.0 mg." },
      { q:"When should a long-term obesity medication be discontinued per the FDA?", opts:["If less than 5% weight loss after 16 weeks","If any weight is regained in week 1","After exactly 3 months regardless of results","Only if side effects occur"], ans:0, exp:"The FDA recommends discontinuation if there is less than 5% weight loss after 16 weeks." },
      { q:"Wadden et al. found the GREATEST weight loss came from which approach over 52 weeks?", opts:["Pharmacotherapy alone (~11 lb / 5.0 kg)","Lifestyle alone (~15 lb / 6.8 kg)","Combined pharmacotherapy and lifestyle (~26 lb / 11.8 kg)","No intervention"], ans:2, exp:"Combined pharmacotherapy plus lifestyle produced the greatest loss, about 26 lb (11.8 kg)." },
      { q:"If Hector later considered bariatric surgery, the ACC/AHA threshold with his comorbidity would be a BMI of at least:", opts:["27 kg/m2","30 kg/m2","35 kg/m2 with an obesity-related comorbidity","45 kg/m2"], ans:2, exp:"Surgery is recommended at BMI >=40, or >=35 with at least one obesity-related comorbidity." }
    ]
  },
  { num:7, topic:"Behavior & Self-monitoring — Sally", scenario:"Sally keeps a journal of activity, food, weight, and feelings. She notes she drank two sugary beverages per day (14/week), each about 140 calories, and that she is less active on busy, stressful workdays.",
    qs:[
      { q:"Cutting from 14 sugary drinks/week to 7 by swapping one daily for water reflects which behavioral strategy?", opts:["Contingency management","Behavioral substitution / stimulus control","Maximal-intensity training","Pharmacotherapy"], ans:1, exp:"Replacing a sugary drink with water is behavioral substitution combined with controlling the stimulus, both CBT strategies in the program." },
      { q:"Sally likely faces which common self-monitoring error?", opts:["Overestimating intake and underestimating activity","Underestimating intake (by ~30-50%) and overestimating activity","Perfectly accurate tracking","Tracking only weight"], ans:1, exp:"Clients tend to underestimate intake by about 30 to 50% and overestimate physical activity." },
      { q:"Her plan to walk 15 minutes during each of two work breaks is an example of:", opts:["High-intensity interval training","Accumulating activity in shorter bouts to reach daily totals","Bariatric preparation","A reason total distance does not matter"], ans:1, exp:"Accumulating activity in shorter bouts is encouraged because total distance/time drives EE and fits busy schedules." },
      { q:"Which approach should the trainer use to keep Sally as the expert in her own goals?", opts:["Prescribe a strict meal plan","Use the ACE Mover Method and ABC Approach with open-ended questions","Tell her exactly what to eat","Avoid discussing her journal"], ans:1, exp:"The trainer uses the ACE Mover Method/ABC Approach, asking open-ended questions so the client sets goals within scope of practice." },
      { q:"Self-monitoring with a food diary has been shown to be effective primarily for:", opts:["Short-term water weight only","Long-term weight loss","Increasing appetite","Replacing exercise"], ans:1, exp:"Keeping a food diary is a self-monitoring strategy shown effective for long-term weight loss (Peterson et al., 2014)." }
